# Firebase Cloud Functions Conventions

## Project Structure

- `functions/models/` -- Firestore CDC triggers (`onDocumentWritten`) and Pub/Sub subscriber handlers
- `functions/ai/` -- LLM-powered logic (prompts, completions, AI algorithms)
- `functions/common/` -- Shared utilities:
  - `pubsub.js` -- Pub/Sub topic constants, `publishMessage`, `publishRipple`
  - `tasks.js` -- Task queue helpers (`queueTask`, `tryQueueTask`)
  - `functions.js` -- Function configs (`defaultConfig`, `gbConfig`, `scrapeConfig`)
  - `database.js` -- Firestore CRUD helpers
  - `utils.js` -- General utilities (`handleChangedRelations`, `retryAsyncFunction`, etc.)
- `functions/services/` -- External service integrations (Twilio, auth)
- `functions/content/` -- Content scraping

## CDC (Change Data Capture) Triggers

Use `onDocumentWritten` with this standard pattern:

```javascript
exports.onEntityUpdate = onDocumentWritten(
    {
      document: "collection/{id}",
      ...defaultConfig,
    },
    async (event) => {
      const before = event.data.before.data();
      const after = event.data.after.data();
      if (!before && !after) return Promise.resolve();

      const _create = !before && after;
      const _delete = before && !after;
      const _update = before && after;

      // Guard each publish with change detection:
      // - Use _.isEqual() for arrays (pids, sids, stids, eids)
      // - Use != or !== for primitives
      if (
        _create && !_.isEmpty(after.pids) ||
        _update && !_.isEqual(before.pids, after.pids) ||
        _delete && !_.isEmpty(before.pids)
      ) {
        await publishMessage(TOPIC_NAME, {before, after});
      }

      return Promise.resolve();
    },
);
```

## Pub/Sub Pattern

- All topic constants are defined in `functions/common/pubsub.js`
- Topic names follow the convention: `on[Entity][Action]` (e.g., `onPostChangedStats`)
- Naming: `CHANGED` = something did change, `SHOULD_CHANGE` = requesting a recalculation
- Use `publishMessage(topic, json)` for standard (non-looping) messages
- Message payloads are simple JSON: either `{id}` or `{before, after}`

### Subscriber pattern:

```javascript
exports.onTopicHandler = onMessagePublished(
    {
      topic: TOPIC_CONSTANT,
      ...defaultConfig,
    },
    async (event) => {
      const data = event.data.message.json;
      // Process...
      return Promise.resolve();
    },
);
```

## Ripple Depth (Loop Prevention)

For pub/sub chains that can oscillate (circular dependencies), use depth-limited ripple:

- `publishRipple(topic, json, depth)` -- depth-aware publisher, auto-decrements depth and stops when exhausted
- Thread depth: destructure `depth` from the message json, then pass it to `publishRipple` (decrement and default to `MAX_RIPPLE_DEPTH` are automatic):
  ```javascript
  const {before, after, depth} = event.data.message.json;
  await publishRipple(TOPIC, {id}, depth);
  ```

**Known circular loops that MUST use `publishRipple`:**
1. Statement <-> Entity confidence: `onStatementChangedConfidence` <-> `onEntityChangedConfidence`
2. Statement <-> Entity bias: `onStatementChangedBias` <-> `onEntityChangedBias`

**Known re-queuing loops that MUST use `_depth` in task messages:**
3. `onPostShouldFindStories` re-queues `POST_SHOULD_FIND_STORIES_TASK` for affected posts (uses `queueRippleTask`)
4. `onPostShouldFindStatements` re-queues `POST_SHOULD_FIND_STATEMENTS_TASK` for affected posts (uses `queueRippleTask`)

If you create a new pub/sub chain that can cycle back to itself, use `publishRipple` instead of `publishMessage`. For task re-queuing loops, use `queueRippleTask` instead of `queueTask`.

## Task Queues

- Use `queueTask(queue, message, delaySeconds)` for direct queuing
- Use `tryQueueTask(collection, id, conditionFn, updates, queue, message, delay)` for conditional queuing with transaction-based deduplication
- Task queue constants are in `functions/common/tasks.js`
- If re-queuing can loop, use `queueRippleTask(queue, message, depth)` -- auto-decrements and stops when exhausted, consistent with `publishRipple`

## Bidirectional Relation Sync

Use `handleChangedRelations(before, after, field, updateFn, idKey, relatedKey, extraUpdates, relationType)`:
- `manyToMany` (default): arrays on both sides (e.g., statement.pids <-> post.stids)
- `oneToMany`: single value on source, array on target (e.g., post.eid -> entity.pids)
- `manyToOne`: array on source, single value on target

## Function Configs

- `defaultConfig` -- 60s timeout, standard memory, 10 max instances
- `gbConfig` -- 60s timeout, 2GiB memory, 10 max instances
- `scrapeConfig` -- 300s timeout, 1 concurrency, 5 max instances, 2GiB memory

## General Rules

- Always use `retryAsyncFunction(() => ...)` for Firestore writes
- Use `lodash` for array comparisons (`_.isEqual`, `_.isEmpty`, `_.uniqBy`)
- Use `FieldValue.arrayUnion` / `FieldValue.arrayRemove` for array field updates
- Use `Timestamp.now().toMillis()` for timestamps
- Return `Promise.resolve()` at the end of handlers
- Log function entry with entity IDs for tracing
